##PSYCHO: The two weeks I suspected I had a new coronary pneumonia

Vicechina  

Function description, different color vision

I have a long-distance relationship with my boyfriend. He is in Wuhan and I am in Hangzhou. In early January, I decided to go to Wuhan on January 10 to spend the weekend with my boyfriend, who might be going abroad in the next year.

Knowing my plan, my colleague and Roommate Xiaorou and Manman sent me a news of the discovery of a new coronavirus. But the development trend of the epidemic is not obvious, in addition to the day on a hot Weibo search, no longer see the relevant official news.

On the afternoon of the 10th, I took a train to Wuhan. Because of my facial allergies (dust and Mites are my allergens) , I used to wear a mask on the way. At the exit of the railway station to buy good food, I called an express car to go to my boyfriend's house.

My boyfriend wanted to take me and my colleagues to have hot pot, but I bought so much food, I decided not to go out. He then turned on the air conditioner and ate his meal in short sleeves before it was fully heated. We played a few games in the evening, to see the weather tomorrow, ready to go shopping Han street, but also searched the delicious barbecue shop.

At about 1 o'clock in the evening, I was lost and could hear my boyfriend getting out of bed and walking around. He was not conscious enough to say that he had a fever. I turned up the Thermostat and thought he had a cold or a stomach flu, but he didn't have diarrhea.

The next day we cancelled our trip to Han Street. He had no temperature, no appetite, and his sore throat and cough were getting worse. He took antipyretics and anti-inflammatories and had a slight fever in the evening.

Two days later, on Sunday, I asked for leave to stay, but he insisted that I go back first. He was no longer feverish, but had fatigue and a cough. I ended up buying tickets for the evening.

It was too early to get to Hankou Station, so I waited in line for hot and dry noodles. The shop was small, with lines of people coming and going, only four tables full of people, and people eating noodles out of paper bowls at the door. Everyone's probably in a hurry. It usually takes less than five minutes.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Old Hankou hot and dry noodle shop

Back to Hangzhou, roommate heard my disappointment in Wuhan also expressed regret.

Since January 13th, the news of pneumonia has become the talk of the town. The boyfriend's back on his feet, so I'm not worried about him. We even thought we had a fever to thank for not leaving the House that day. Looking back on all the details of my success in avoiding infection, I'm almost glad to jump.

At that time, there was absolutely no information about quarantine and containment of infection. I didn't think much of the train ride, the trip to Hankou station, the hot-and-dry noodles.

January 14th, company annual meeting. In the evening, I came out wearing a coat, accidentally blew the wind, during the dinner felt headache, so with her roommate Xiaorou left early. I waited a long time for a taxi. When I got home, I was shaking, my head was pounding, and I fell into a deep sleep. In the early morning, I began to have a fever. The air conditioner was on at 29 degrees and I still felt cold. The next day Xiao Rou accompanied me to the pharmacy downstairs. My temperature was 37.5 and I bought some cold cream.

At the regular meeting, I had a bad cough. Two Times I coughed and blushed. I went out continuously for fear of disturbing everyone. The colleague sitting next to me was careful, but asked me jokingly, "you can't be the pneumonia in Wuhan. " I smiled and added, "it's possible. I went to Wuhan on the weekend. " I'd be straight out of here doing a sweep. But at the time, with flu season, flu symptoms were so common, there were several patients with colds and fevers in the office, and everyone laughed and guessed who was next.

My throat was still a little worse, my throat was sore as if it had been split open, I had difficulty swallowing, the whole tube was pulled and pulled, but there was no difficulty in breathing, and I carried on as if I had a cold. After three days, I started to feel better. I asked for leave early and went home.

On the 20th, I wore a mask all the way back to Heze. After two days, go shopping with the family, eat, calm before the holiday routine.

On the 22nd, reports of pneumonia began to pour in, peppered with reports of cases and reminders to wear masks and wash hands. This Day the company official holiday, a colleague in the group said, downstairs all sold out of face masks pharmacy. I was hoarding disposable surgical masks because of allergies, and my colleagues were snapping them up.

On the 23rd, the number of suspected and confirmed cases shot up overnight. Wuhan announced the closure of the Han corridor, our community and town began to count the number of people returning from the field, paste a conscious isolation initiative. Mom went to the supermarket and grabbed some bottles of disinfectant.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Community Flyers

So far, I had nothing to worry about until I got a message from my roommates.

Sheo-rou first asked me if my cough was getting better, and then urged me to go to the hospital for a check-up. She feared that if she came into contact with an infected person, the risk would double again once she returned home, where there were elderly people with low resistance.

Another roommate, Manman, also began to panic, from group chat to private chat, a little pleading tone, let me go for a check.

Screenshots of my conversations with my friends

I know it's no use explaining "I wear a mask when I go out" at this point. I have to prove that I'm not sick, I have to prove that I'm not infected, and I have to prove that I'm still me after Wuhan.

I stayed up all night on the 23rd with a chill in my back. I began to doubt my own explanation, and even began to waver: Is it really only because of a cold for a cough?

On the 24th, the eve of the Lunar New Year, I made an excuse and went straight to the city hospital. On my way to the emergency room, I felt my heart beat for the first time. I wanted to walk quickly, but I was afraid, as if I was waiting for a verdict.

At the triage desk in the emergency department sat two doctors, both in protective clothing. I went over and said, "I want to check, I went to Wuhan on the 12th. " The two doctors immediately got serious and called a supervisor, sister Wang. Sister Wang immediately put on her goggles and sat down, barely looking at me, and took out a pen and paper.

"Name. "

"Age. "

"ID number. "

"where do you live? "

"symptoms of what? "

"When did you go to Wuhan? "

"What Day did you return to Heze? " 

"phone number. "

After the interview, they called the fever clinic and told me to go there.

The fever clinic opened two rooms on the same day and was crowded with patients, some wearing double masks. We stare at each other cautiously, covered in caution and suspicion.

"Don't you have a fever? " The doctor asked the woman in front of me.

"No, I don't have a fever. I came back from Wuhan on the 20th. "

"What are your symptoms? "

"cough, headache. "

"So you want to get tested? "

The woman insisted on a test, and the doctor ordered a CBC, c-protein response, Procalcitonin, a viral test, and a chest CT.. After typing the payment confirmation form, the follow-up team cut in a man to let the doctor see the blood test report.

"Your report is nothing. It's a common cold. "

"That is very good, that I go back to take what medicine? " The man feels relieved, even the facial expression that the brow can see when smiling. After the doctor had prescribed the medicine, the woman in front of me began to tell her story.

"Doctor, I also came back from Wuhan on the 16th. "

"Do you have a fever? "

"No fever. "

The doctor sighed and turned to the man in front of me. "Are you from Wuhan, too? "

He nodded, and I nodded.

The doctor stood up, counted the number roughly, and shouted to the patients in the room, "are you all from Wuhan? "

"uh-huh. " "Yes. " "I am. " There was a tidy response, about two-thirds of it.

The doctor sat down, sighed, and expertly wrote out the same checklist for all three of us, then called the nurse at the door to deliver the printout to her, as if she'd run out of printer paper.

Hospital line

I took the bill to the self-service machine to scan the Qr Code, the amount of 918.9 yuan let me hesitate for a moment. The man in front of me was paying the bill on another self-service machine. He picked up the phone and called his wife. "CHECK IT TO BE 1,000 smaller! Should I check? " After discussion, the man walked out of the fever clinic.

A screenshot of the hospital bill and my lab report

I went back into the exam room to cut in line and ask if I could cancel the chest CT and just do the blood work. The two old men blushed in front of them and were reprimanding the visitors for jumping the queue. The doctor writes out a check-up sheet at the same time placatory old person, "the person that visit a doctor is really too much" . The old man shouted, "let the nurse at the door shout! "

While waiting in line for blood, the girl at the back asked me, "you're two days out of the observation period, why do you want to check? " I said I was afraid.

It's 3:00 in the afternoon after the blood draw. I worried that the report might not come out today, pacing up and down in front of the hot door, anxious. I do not know is the mask to stay for a long time hair stuffy, or has been in a state of nervous tension, I even feel short of breath chest tightness several times.

Finally, around 4:30, the CBC report came back: No abnormalities. C Protein response was normal. I went back into the fever clinic with these two reports and a chest CT, and I was in the first line for follow-up.

Toward the end of the day, and on New Year's Eve, the room was filled with impatience, dissatisfaction, and trepidation. The line for follow up appointments began to blur, with many new patients scrambling to get to the doctor as fast as they could, and people with reports swarmed around the doctor, reaching out for a corner and rushing to hand them over. I tried to hand it over a couple of times, but it just ran over me.

At about 5 o'clock, I finally handed the report to the doctor and heard the words "all is well" . Still breathless, he added, "chest CT shows a small shadow. Come back tomorrow with a full report. "

It's the best I can do. I rushed out of the hospital to make New Year's Eve dinner at home. MOM GETS OFF at 6:00. I have to make this meal.

I had something on my mind that I couldn't talk about, and I wanted to find out before I told my family. After dinner I absentmindedly watched TV with my mother and kept swiping the results on my phone. By the next day, most of the results were back, and the chest CT showed mild inflammation, except for one viral test that was negative, and everything else was normal. I slightly reduce the tension, cut a few pictures sent to the group, the initial proof of my "innocence. ".

Four of my inspection reports

Unexpectedly, on the afternoon of the 25th, I saw the news: a case was confirmed in Heze. It was confirmed on the afternoon of the 24th at the fever clinic. The news also said, "do not blindly go to the hospital during the epidemic check-up, " I suddenly back sweating, heart rate accelerated.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
News of confirmed cases

And so, once again, I was a suspect.

I'm not going to my follow-up. I'm starting isolation at home. I returned to Hangzhou at the end of February after 14 days and 14 days of fear, until my family had passed the incubation period. Access control is already tight, but my only address for the last 15-30 days is Heze, Shandong. Health Code and Behavior Track proved my innocence, I have been to Wuhan is no longer a matter of doubt.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A screenshot of the behavioral trajectory

Now sheo-rou still talks about the shock she had a month ago. "You know what? Your symptoms years ago are too much like the new crown infection. The more I think about it, the more scared I am. "

So Am I? Especially when I read about how some people who had been to Wuhan were treated, even those who had not been back for a long time were reported by the residents'committee and then forcibly quarantined, I understood that it could have been me.

Which scares me more? I can't tell you what it's like to be infected or what it's like to be infected.
